## GitHub Pages project-subpath path-prefix bug + deploy-lag vs browser-cache discrimination (gm site method)

A client-side fetch base built as a root-absolute path (e.g. const API_BASE='/docs/api') 404s under a GitHub Pages PROJECT subpath because root-absolute ignores the /<project>/ prefix the Pages site is served under. Fix: derive the base relative to the deployed page from location.href, stripping the known leaf so it resolves to /<project>/docs/api on Pages AND /docs/api at root: SITE_ROOT = location.href.split('#')[0].split('?')[0].replace(/(?:stats(?:\.html)?|index\.html)?\/?$/,''); base = SITE_ROOT + 'docs/api'. Also ensure the Pages build copies the data dir into the deployed subpath (gh-pages.yml: cp docs/api/*.json dist/docs/api/).

Discrimination method when a live browser-witness still shows the OLD behavior after a confirmed push: a raw fetch of the deployed HTML showing the NEW source while the browser verb's page.evaluate shows OLD network paths is a browser-CACHE hit, NOT deploy-lag. Eliminate by re-navigating with a cache-busting query param (?cb=N); if the cache-busted load then shows the fixed paths and 200s, the deploy IS live and the prior failure was stale cache. Process-of-elimination: raw-HTML-fetch vs cache-busted-browser-evaluate are two witnesses that separate deploy-lag from browser-cache.